  "prompt": "What are the five basic data type in c?",
  "response": "In the C programming language, there are five basic (fundamental or primary) data types:\n\n1. Integer (int)\n- Used to store whole numbers\n- Examples: -5, 0, 10, 100\n- Typically occupies 4 bytes of memory\n- Variations include short, long, and unsigned integers\n\n2. Character (char)\n- Used to store single characters\n- Occupies 1 byte of memory\n- Can store ASCII values\n- Examples: 'A', 'b', '5'\n\n3. Float\n- Used to store decimal/floating-point numbers\n- Occupies 4 bytes of memory\n- Provides single-precision floating-point values\n- Examples: 3.14, -0.5, 2.0\n\n4. Double\n- Used to store decimal/floating-point numbers\n- Occupies 8 bytes of memory\n- Provides double-precision floating-point values\n- More precise than float\n- Examples: 3.14159, -0.00001, 2.5\n\n5. Void\n- Represents the absence of a value\n- Used for functions that do not return a value\n- Used as a generic pointer type\n- Used in function declarations that don't return anything\n\nThese basic data types form the foundation for more complex data types in C.",
